n1: Generative AI
	description=Produces new content rather than merely sorting existing data. This course draws the line around transformer-style text generation.
n2: Classification and prediction AI
	description=Spam filters, recommenders, fraud detectors. Useful contrast object: plenty of AI is not generative.
n3: 4D human side
	description=Human competencies respond to machine properties. The framework matters because the user is the other half of the system.
n4: Pretraining
	description=Reads vast text and learns one thing: what token plausibly comes next.
n5: Document completer
	description=The raw system after pretraining. Fluent continuation machine, not yet an assistant.
n6: Fine-tuning
	description=Human preference shaping turns completion into assistant behavior: answer helpfully, decline harmful asks, stay within norms.
n7: Helpful assistant
	description=The interaction layer people meet. Useful, polite, often cooperative, never free of the mechanism beneath it.
n8: Sycophancy
	description=The model leans toward validating the user's frame unless asked, or forced, to disagree.
n9: Verbosity default
	description=Left alone, the assistant often gives more than the task strictly needs.
n10: Over-caution
	description=Safety shaping can produce refusals or hedging that are broader than the true hazard.
n11: Loose confidence calibration
	description=Tone and truth are only loosely coupled. Smooth prose can wrap a guess.
n12: Next Token Prediction
	description=The core generator. Fluency comes from it, and hallucination comes from it too.
n13: Well-worn path
	description=Summaries, reformats, common explanations, code shapes the model has seen many times.
n14: Specificity zone
	description=The danger band where fabrication concentrates: precise facts that can sound right without being right.
n15: Knowledge
	description=What the model absorbed during training and nothing beyond that without tools.
n16: Knowledge cutoff
	description=Training stopped at some point. After that date, default knowledge is frozen.
n17: Source amnesia
	description=The model may know a thing without knowing where it came from in a citeable way.
n18: Working memory
	description=Fixed context window. The model only attends to what still fits inside the current workspace.
n19: Lost in the middle
	description=Attention is not uniform. Middle material gets weaker than edges.
n20: No persistent memory by default
	description=Corrections do not retrain the model. New session, new blank slate.
n21: Steerability
	description=The system follows instructions through pattern matching, not deep semantic understanding.
n22: Tight control zone
	description=Format, tone, role, and bounded structure are where steerability feels strongest.
n23: Letter over spirit
	description=The instruction can be satisfied literally while missing the reason the instruction existed.
n24: Reasoning drift
	description=Long chains accumulate small errors. The final answer can preserve the early mistake faithfully.
n25: Hallucinated citations
	description=Citation-shaped output appears because plausible pattern outruns actual knowledge.
n26: Stale answers
	description=True-then becomes false-now, yet the answer still arrives with composure.
n27: Long-conversation drift
	description=Good constraints dissolve as context grows and the important bits slide into the dead zone.
n28: Confidently wrong math
	description=Fluent reasoning does not guarantee precise arithmetic or logic.
n29: Agreeable bad premise
	description=The assistant inherits the user's false framing and decorates it instead of resisting it.
n30: Citations and source grounding
	description=Makes the generator show what is backed by an external source and what is merely fluent synthesis.
n31: Web search and retrieval
	description=Pulls in information the base model never had or had too unevenly.
n32: Projects, memory, and standing context
	description=Moves recurring facts and constraints closer to the active window so the user stops repeating themselves.
n33: Mid-process checkpoints
	description=Breaks a brittle chain into inspectable segments before one hidden error poisons the whole run.
n34: Code execution and structured output
	description=Gives math, parsing, and schema-constrained tasks a stricter substrate than free-form text.
n35: Uncertainty signaling
	description=Useful when honest, but never a substitute for checking the high-risk specifics yourself.
n36: Calibrated trust
	description=Do not trust or distrust the machine wholesale. Place the task on each continuum and respond to that shape.
n37: Verify specifics independently
	description=Names, dates, numbers, URLs, citations, quotes. Precision is where fluency most often impersonates truth.
n38: Supply the missing knowledge and context
	description=If the model is thin, stale, or forgetful on your domain, bring the material yourself.
n39: State the goal, not just the format
	description=A machine can obey a surface instruction and still miss the win condition. Goal language closes that gap.
n40: Diagnose property pairs
	description=Most bad outputs are not one property failing alone. The pair tells you which fix actually matters.
n41: Durable mental model
	description=Model quality moves; the structure remains. The point is not memorizing edge cases but seeing the machine through a stable lens.
